What was captured, and what was changed
---------------------------------------
`scripts/capture_real_page_snapshot.py` reproduces both files. It makes one
request, sends the project's explicit User-Agent, and checks the path against
w3.org/robots.txt before fetching (the path is allowed).

The snapshot is the DOM **after** load, serialized, with two deliberate edits:

  1. The one same-origin stylesheet is inlined as a `<style>` element. Every
     extractor here reads *rendered* text, so the CSS has to travel with the
     snapshot or the file would extract differently offline than the page did
     live. This is why the snapshot (170,878 bytes) is larger than the page's
     original markup (57,170 characters).
  2. All `<script>` elements are removed, *after* they have already run. The DOM
     they built is preserved; the file stays static and deterministic.

Images and fonts keep their absolute URLs. They affect neither rendered text nor
the accessibility tree, so they cannot move an extracted referent; they simply
fail to load when the snapshot is scanned offline.

